MEH BOT: Maximizing Emotional Help By Organizing Text 🤖¶

By: Rohan Mathur, Ritik Chopra, Arnav Mittal

Purpose ⭐¶

Mental health is an often overlooked portion of our daily lives and as such a major goal of this project is to provide aid to ones own mental strife as a consequence of daily general inconveniences.

Inspirational quotes have been a part of our culture for a long time. We can find examples of this in t-shirts, decorations, as well as online images.

Giving (at least a little) happiness through the form of tailored inspirational quotes could go a long way.

We wanted to create a bot that has the capability of generating text that would help other people feel better. Our goal was to provide a way to receive emotional relief through the use of this bot (or at least a starting framework to do so). Everyone has problems, we were hoping to provide an aid to those problems.

Generating Helpful Quotes 🪔¶

In this model, we are using the Inspirational Quotes dataset, https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mattimansha/inspirational-quotes in order to generate new phrases that would be comparable to a quote that has already been said. The idea is to take the queries that have been provided and relate them to already existing inspirational quotes. That way we can hope to produce a response that can give comfort to a user.

Import the libraries 📚¶

As the first step, we need to import the required libraries:

We make use of several tensorflow libraries that will be discussed later. It should be noted that we are using tensorflows sequential model for the processing of our data. Considering that we are processing a sequence of sentences, the need to understand previous sentiments of the sentence requires the use of a sequential model.

Dataset Cleaning 🧹¶

We want to clean up our data set. This includes lowercasing all characters, encoding of text in UTF-8, and decoding of text as ASCII.

This means that we want to cleanse the data of any unusual characters to be decoded into normal ASCII characters.

In [4]:
def clean_text(txt):
    txt = "".join(v for v in txt).lower()
    txt = txt.encode("utf8").decode("ascii",'ignore')
    return txt 

corpus = [clean_text(x) for x in quotes]
corpus[:10]

Generating Sequence of N Combinations of Tokens 🪙¶

In text generation, we want to predict the next word/token based on the given input sequence of tokens/words.

This leads us to Tokenization of our current input quotes. This is the process of extracting tokens (terms / words) from a corpus (collection of documents). The Tensorflow library has a tokenization model that can be used to obtain the tokens and their index in the corpus. This step allows every entry in the dataset to be converted into sequence of tokens.

In [5]:
tokenizer = Tokenizer(filters='!"#$%&()*+-/:;<=>@[\\]^_`{|}~\t\n',)

def get_sequence_of_tokens(corpus):
    ## tokenization
    new_corpus = []
    for x in corpus:
      to_tokenize = ['.',',',':',';','!','?']
      end_tokenize = [' .',' ,',' :',' ;',' !',' ?']
      for i, v in enumerate(to_tokenize):
        x = x.replace(v, end_tokenize[i])
      new_corpus.append(x)
    corpus = new_corpus

    tokenizer.fit_on_texts(corpus)
    total_words = len(tokenizer.word_index) + 1
    
    ## convert data to sequence of tokens 
    input_sequences = []
    for line in corpus:
        token_list = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([line])[0]
        for i in range(1, len(token_list)):
            n_gram_sequence = token_list[:i+1]
            input_sequences.append(n_gram_sequence)
    return input_sequences, total_words

inp_sequences, total_words = get_sequence_of_tokens(corpus)
inp_sequences[:10]

🅿adding, 🅿redictors, and 🅿-Labels¶

Previously we created a combinations in upto N tokens in our n-gram tokenization step. These combinations all have different lengths and need to be equal before we pass them into our model. To do this, we are going to use the pad_sequence function of Keras within Tensorflow and we will add the padding to the beginning of each sequence. To create the predictors and labels for our model, we use the first N-1 tokens as predictors and the last token as the label.

In [7]:
def generate_padded_sequences(input_sequences):
    max_sequence_len = max([len(x) for x in input_sequences])
    input_sequences = np.array(pad_sequences(input_sequences, maxlen=max_sequence_len, padding='pre'))
    
    predictors, label = input_sequences[:,:-1],input_sequences[:,-1]
    label = ku.to_categorical(label, num_classes=total_words)
    return predictors, label, max_sequence_len

predictors, label, max_sequence_len = generate_padded_sequences(inp_sequences)

LSTMs and GRUs for Text Generation 🟡 (IFYKYK)¶

In a Recurrent Neural Network the output of a layer is used as the input for the same or lower layer. This creates loops in the neural network architecture, acting as a 'memory state' of the neurons. This state allows the neurons an ability to remember what have been learned so far. In theory an RNN can learn long term memory but in practice it cannot. This means that the idea of a traditional RNN suffers from vanishing gradients. In this problem, while learning with a large number of layers, eventually the gradients may become very small and do not make a significant change when updating the weights for the next layer. To mitigate this issue, LSTMs (Long Short Term Memory) were developed.

Input embedding layer

  • When considering natural language processing, this layer allows us to capture and store syntactic similarities

GRU Layer

  • LSTMs use an input, forget, and output gates
  • GRUs use solely an update and reset layer to accomplish the same feat
  • GRUs are less complex making them more effective on smaller datasets like ours
  • Tanh activation, but on recursion uses sigmoid
  • It uses the gates on the previous hidden state to determine which parts to update and which parts to ignore.

Dropout Layer

  • Temporarily deactivates a certain number of neurons, and avoids them during backpropagation
  • Used a dropout of 0.5
  • Reduces overfitting

Dense Layer

  • We use the softmax function
  • Fully connects to ensure appropriate output

Compilation

  • The model is compiled through categorical cross entropy loss and the ADAM optimizer

Sources:

  • https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/keras/layers/GRU
  • https://www.superdatascience.com/blogs/recurrent-neural-networks-rnn-the-vanishing-gradient-problem/
  • https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/understanding-embedding-layer-in-keras-bbe3ff1327ce
  • https://www.mathworks.com/help/deeplearning/ref/nnet.cnn.layer.grulayer.html

In [8]:
def create_model(max_sequence_len, total_words):
    input_len = max_sequence_len - 1
    model = tf.keras.models.Sequential()
    
    # Add Input Embedding Layer
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Embedding(total_words, 512, input_length=input_len))
    
    # Add Hidden Layer 1 - GRU Layer
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.GRU(512))
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5))
    
    # Add Output Layer
    model.add(Dense(total_words, activation='softmax'))

    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    return model

model = create_model(max_sequence_len, total_words)
model.summary()
dot_img_file = './model_1.png'
tf.keras.utils.plot_model(model, to_file=dot_img_file, show_shapes=True)

Lets train our model now 🚆¶

How did we train the model?

  • We use a callback monitoring the loss that will stop the training after 3 epochs if the loss does not improve (stops training if the loss starts increasing)
  • We train the model over 25 epochs
  • We left shuffle=True in our model.fit to reduce bias (random starting point)

Overfitting

  • When we trained for 100 epochs, it overfit the data. In our case, this meant it generated sequences of random words that happened to appear frequently in the training data

Generating the text 🖊¶

We are going to generate text by sequentially predicting the next word following the given input text. We first tokenize the input text, pad the tokenized sequences and then pass that into the trained model to get predicted word. Our final output is our predicted words strung together. We do this until a punctuation is predicted as the next token.

In [10]:
def generate_text(seed_text, model, max_sequence_len):
    output_word = ""
    while output_word != "." and output_word != "!" and output_word != "?":
        token_list = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([seed_text])[0]
        token_list = pad_sequences([token_list], maxlen=max_sequence_len-1, padding='pre')
        predict_x=model.predict(token_list,verbose=0) 
        predicted=np.argmax(predict_x, axis=1)
        
        output_word = ""
        for word,index in tokenizer.word_index.items():
            if index == predicted:
                output_word = word
                break
        seed_text += " "+output_word
    return seed_text.title()

Results ✅¶

Here are our results after we trained our model and used it to generate text based on specific outputs. We had an accuracy of 71.95% and a loss of 1.0682. From the sentences, we can see a mix of good and bad sentences. Some sentences like A Rainbow In Someone'S Cloud . could be a conceivable response to the question we asked. The sentence isnt perfect grammatically, but the message behind the sentence answers the question we asked. On the other hand, we have some sentences like Not Afraid , But I Am About To Me . which dont answer the question asked at all. These sentences read like a random jumble of words or even an answer to a different question.

Improvement Ideas 🤔¶

How can we improve our model in the future?

  • We could add more layers to the model (learn more specific features)
  • We could fine tune the parameters of our layers in the model (number of
    nodes, etc.)
  • We could experiment more with the number of epochs and the stopping case for the callback function (what it is monitoring and its patience)
